    <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-7.2</fr:parent>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>We immediately deduce from the definition (<fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.8" href="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.8.xml" number="1.3.8" />) that the first direct filtration of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_r(K,W)]]></fr:tex> is the filtration <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F_d]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_r(K,W)]]></fr:tex> by the images
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       F_d^p(E_r(K,W))       = \operatorname {Im} \big (E_r(F^pK,W) \to  E_r(K,W)\big ).     ]]></fr:tex>
    Dually, the second direct filtration (<fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.9" href="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.9.xml" number="1.3.9" />) of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_r(K,W)]]></fr:tex> is the filtration <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F_{d^*}]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_r(K,W)]]></fr:tex> by the kernels
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       F_{d^*}^p(E_r(K,W))       = \operatorname {Ker} \big (E_r(K,W) \to  E_r(K/F^pK,W)\big ).     ]]></fr:tex>
    The recurrent filtration <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F_{\mathrm {rec}}]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_r(K,W)]]></fr:tex> is intermediary between these two filtrations ((iii) of <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.13" href="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.13.xml" taxon="Proposition" number="1.3.13" />).</fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter>
  <fr:backmatter>
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
      <fr:frontmatter>
        <fr:title text="Context">Context</fr:title>
        <fr:authors />
      </fr:frontmatter>
      <fr:mainmatter>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>2684</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-7.2</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-7.2.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Hodge Theory III › Supplements to §1 › Supplements to the two filtrations lemma"><fr:link type="local" href="hodge-theory-iii-7.xml" addr="hodge-theory-iii-7" title="Hodge Theory III › Supplements to §1"><fr:link type="local" href="hodge-theory-iii.xml" addr="hodge-theory-iii" title="Hodge Theory III">Hodge Theory III</fr:link> › Supplements to §1</fr:link> › Supplements to the two filtrations lemma</fr:title>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:number>7.2</fr:number>
            <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-7</fr:parent>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>In this section, we give a new proof of the two filtrations lemma (<fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.16" href="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.16.xml" taxon="Theorem" number="1.3.16" />) and some supplements.</fr:p>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>1049</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-7.2.1</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-7.2.1.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>7.2.1</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-7.2</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(K,F,W)]]></fr:tex> be a bounded-below bifiltered complex with objects in an abelian category <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathscr {A}]]></fr:tex>, with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> assumed to be biregular.</fr:p>
                <fr:p>We say that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(K,F,W)]]></fr:tex> is <fr:em><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex>-splitable</fr:em> if the filtered complex <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(K,W)]]></fr:tex> can be written as a sum of filtered complexes
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       (K,W)       = \bigoplus _{n\in \mathbb {Z}} (K_n,W_n)     ]]></fr:tex>
    with
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       F^nK       = \bigoplus _{n'\geqslant  n} K_{n'}.     ]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r_0\geqslant 0]]></fr:tex> be an integer or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[+\infty ]]></fr:tex>.
  The following condition was considered in <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.16" href="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.16.xml" taxon="Theorem" number="1.3.16" /> and <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.17" href="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.17.xml" taxon="Corollary" number="1.3.17" />:</fr:p>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>1050</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-7.2.2</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-7.2.2.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Condition</fr:taxon>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>7.2.2</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-7.2</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>For every non-negative integer <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r<r_0]]></fr:tex>, the differentials <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d_r]]></fr:tex> of the graded complex <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_r(K,W)]]></fr:tex> are strictly compatible with the recurrent filtration defined by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>1051</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-7.2.3</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-7.2.3.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>7.2.3</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-7.2</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>It is clear that, if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(K,F,W)]]></fr:tex> is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex>-splitable, then <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-7.2.2" href="hodge-theory-iii-7.2.2.xml" taxon="Condition" number="7.2.2" /> is satisfied for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r_0=\infty ]]></fr:tex>.
    Conversely, it seems that if <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-7.2.2" href="hodge-theory-iii-7.2.2.xml" taxon="Condition" number="7.2.2" /> is satisfied for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r_0=\infty ]]></fr:tex>, then everything is as if the functor <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Gr}_F]]></fr:tex> were exact.
    For example, we will show that the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Gr}_F]]></fr:tex> of the spectral sequence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E(K,W)]]></fr:tex> can then be identified with the spectral sequence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E(\operatorname {Gr}_FK,W)]]></fr:tex>, and that the spectral sequence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E(K,F)]]></fr:tex> degenerates (<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_1=E_\infty ]]></fr:tex>).</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>1052</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-7.2.4</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-7.2.4.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>7.2.4</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-7.2</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>We immediately deduce from the definition (<fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.8" href="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.8.xml" number="1.3.8" />) that the first direct filtration of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_r(K,W)]]></fr:tex> is the filtration <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F_d]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_r(K,W)]]></fr:tex> by the images
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       F_d^p(E_r(K,W))       = \operatorname {Im} \big (E_r(F^pK,W) \to  E_r(K,W)\big ).     ]]></fr:tex>
    Dually, the second direct filtration (<fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.9" href="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.9.xml" number="1.3.9" />) of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_r(K,W)]]></fr:tex> is the filtration <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F_{d^*}]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_r(K,W)]]></fr:tex> by the kernels
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       F_{d^*}^p(E_r(K,W))       = \operatorname {Ker} \big (E_r(K,W) \to  E_r(K/F^pK,W)\big ).     ]]></fr:tex>
    The recurrent filtration <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F_{\mathrm {rec}}]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_r(K,W)]]></fr:tex> is intermediary between these two filtrations ((iii) of <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.13" href="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.13.xml" taxon="Proposition" number="1.3.13" />).</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>1053</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-7.2.5</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-7.2.5.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>7.2.5</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-7.2</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Suppose that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(K,F,W)]]></fr:tex> satisfies <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-7.2.2" href="hodge-theory-iii-7.2.2.xml" taxon="Condition" number="7.2.2" /> for some <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r_0\geqslant 0]]></fr:tex>.
    Then

    
 <html:ol xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(i) &quot;">
        <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(F^aK/F^bK,F,W)]]></fr:tex> also satisfies <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-7.2.2" href="hodge-theory-iii-7.2.2.xml" taxon="Condition" number="7.2.2" /> for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r_0]]></fr:tex>.
      </html:li>

      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(ii) &quot;">
        For <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r\leqslant  r_0]]></fr:tex>, the sequence
        <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[           0           \to  E_r(F^pK,W)           \to  E_r(K,W)           \to  E_r(K/F^pK,W)           \to  0         ]]></fr:tex>
        is exact;
        for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r=r_0+1]]></fr:tex>, the sequence
        <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[           E_r(F^pK,W)           \to  E_r(K,W)           \to  E_r(K/F^pK,W)         ]]></fr:tex>
        is exact.
        In particular, for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r\leqslant  r_0+1]]></fr:tex>, the two direct filtrations and the recurrent filtration of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_r(K,W)]]></fr:tex> agree.
      </html:li>

    </html:ol></fr:p>
  
    
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1057</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">#248</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-248.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-7.2.5</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>Fix an integer <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>.
      We will prove the claim

      <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1058</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">#247</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-247.xml</fr:route><fr:authors /><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-7.2.5</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p><fr:em><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(*)_r]]></fr:tex> If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r\leqslant  r_0]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_r(F^pK,W)]]></fr:tex> injects into <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_r(K,W)]]></fr:tex>;
            if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r\leqslant  r_0+1]]></fr:tex>, then its image is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F_\mathrm {rec}(E_r(K,W))]]></fr:tex>.</fr:em></fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

      by induction on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>

    <fr:p>The claim <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(*)_0]]></fr:tex> is always true.
      Assume <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(*)_r]]></fr:tex>, and let us prove <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(*)_{r+1}]]></fr:tex>.
      We can suppose that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[0\leqslant  r\leqslant  r_0]]></fr:tex>.
      We have a diagram
      
      
  <fr:embedded-tex hash="9bf138721e077a2daba6d04461a1d5f7"><fr:embedded-tex-preamble><![CDATA[
    \usepackage {amsmath}
    \usepackage {amssymb}
    \usepackage {tikz-cd}
  ]]></fr:embedded-tex-preamble><fr:embedded-tex-body><![CDATA[\begin {tikzcd}
        E_r(K,W)
          \ar [r,"d_r"]
        & E_r(K,W)
          \ar [r,"d_r"]
        & E_r(K,W)
      \\E_r(F^pK,W)
          \ar [r]
          \ar [u,hook]
        & E_r(F^pK,W)
          \ar [r]
          \ar [u,hook]
        & E_r(F^pK,W)
          \ar [u,hook,swap,"i"]
      \end {tikzcd}]]></fr:embedded-tex-body></fr:embedded-tex>


      
      and the image of the vertical inclusions is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F_\mathrm {rec}^p(E_r(K,W))]]></fr:tex>.
      Since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i]]></fr:tex> is injective,

      <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         \begin {aligned}           F_\mathrm {rec}^p(E_{r+1}(K,W))           &= \operatorname {Im}\Big ( \operatorname {Ker} \big (F_\mathrm {rec}^pE_r(K,W)\xrightarrow {d_r}E_r(K,W) \big ) \to  E_{r+1}(K,W) \Big )         \\&= \operatorname {Im}\Big ( \operatorname {Ker}\big ( E_r(F^pK,W)\xrightarrow {d_r}E_r(F^pK,W) \big ) \to  E_{r+1}(K,W) \Big )         \\&= \operatorname {Im}\big ( E_{r+1}(F^pK,W) \to  E_{r+1}(K,W) \big ).         \end {aligned}       ]]></fr:tex>

      If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r<r_0]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d_r]]></fr:tex> is strictly compatible with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F_\mathrm {rec}]]></fr:tex>, whence
      <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         d_rE_r(K,W)\cap  E_r(F^pK,W)         = d_rE_r(F^pK,W)       ]]></fr:tex>
      and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_{r+1}(F^pK,W)]]></fr:tex> thus injects into <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_{r+1}(K,W)]]></fr:tex>.
      This proves <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(*)_{r+1}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>

    <fr:p>The statements <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(*)_r]]></fr:tex>, combined with the dual statements, implies (ii).</fr:p>

    <fr:p>It follows from (ii) that, for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r<r_0]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\leqslant  b]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_r(F^bK,W)]]></fr:tex> injects into <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_r(F^aK,W)]]></fr:tex>, and that the differential <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d_r]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_r(F^aK,W)]]></fr:tex> is strictly compatible with the first direct filtration of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_r(F^aK,W)]]></fr:tex>.
      We thus deduce, by induction on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r<r_0]]></fr:tex>, that the first direct filtration of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_r(F^aK,W)]]></fr:tex> coincides with the recurrent filtration, and (i) then follows.</fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
  
</fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>1059</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-7.2.6</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-7.2.6.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>7.2.6</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-7.2</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>If <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-7.2.2" href="hodge-theory-iii-7.2.2.xml" taxon="Condition" number="7.2.2" /> is satisfied for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r_0]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r\leqslant  r_0+1]]></fr:tex>, then we denote by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> the filtration <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F_d=F_{d^*}=F_\mathrm {rec}]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_r(W,K)]]></fr:tex>.
    The exact sequences from (ii) of <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-7.2.5" href="hodge-theory-iii-7.2.5.xml" taxon="Proposition" number="7.2.5" />

    
  <fr:embedded-tex hash="f04341f3dc3e7b3f49c6cd0a384d802b"><fr:embedded-tex-preamble><![CDATA[
    \usepackage {amsmath}
    \usepackage {amssymb}
    \usepackage {tikz-cd}
  ]]></fr:embedded-tex-preamble><fr:embedded-tex-body><![CDATA[\begin {tikzcd}
      0
      & E_r(K/F^pK,W)
        \ar [l]
      && E_r(K/F^{p+1}K,W)
        \ar [ll]
      && 0
    \\&& E_r(K,W)
        \ar [ul]
        \ar [ur]
      && E_r(\operatorname {Gr}_F^pK,W)
        \ar [ul]
        \ar [ur]
    \\0
        \ar [r]
      & E_r(F^{p+1}K,W)
        \ar [rr]
        \ar [ur]
      && E_r(F^pK,W)
        \ar [ul]
        \ar [ur]
      && 0
        \ar [ul]
    \end {tikzcd}]]></fr:embedded-tex-body></fr:embedded-tex>


    define, for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r\leqslant  r_0]]></fr:tex>, an (autodual) isomorphism that is compatible with the differentials <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d_r]]></fr:tex>, namely

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1060</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-7.2.6.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-7.2.6.1.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>7.2.6.1</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-7.2.6</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         \operatorname {Gr}_F^p(E_r(K,W))         \simeq  E_r(\operatorname {Gr}_F^pK,W)         \qquad \text {for }r\leqslant  r_0.       \tag{7.2.6.1}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>1061</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-7.2.7</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-7.2.7.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>7.2.7</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-7.2</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>If <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-7.2.2" href="hodge-theory-iii-7.2.2.xml" taxon="Condition" number="7.2.2" /> is satisfied for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r_0=\infty ]]></fr:tex>, then the sequences
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       0       \to  E_r(F^pK,W)       \to  E_r(K,W)       \to  E_r(K/F^pK,W)       \to  0     ]]></fr:tex>
    are exact for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r]]></fr:tex>.
    If the filtration <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[W]]></fr:tex> is biregular, then the sequence
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       0       \to  E_\infty (F^pK,W)       \to  E_\infty (K,W)       \to  E_\infty (K/F^pK,W)       \to  0     ]]></fr:tex>
    is thus exact.
    We can rewrite this sequence as
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       0       \to  \operatorname {Gr}_W(\operatorname {H}(F^pK))       \to  \operatorname {Gr}_W(\operatorname {H}(K))       \to  \operatorname {Gr}_W(\operatorname {H}(K/F^pK))       \to  0.     ]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
                <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
                  <fr:frontmatter>
                    <fr:anchor>1062</fr:anchor>
                    <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-7.2.7.1</fr:addr>
                    <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-7.2.7.1.xml</fr:route>
                    <fr:taxon>Lemma</fr:taxon>
                    <fr:authors />
                    <fr:number>7.2.7.1</fr:number>
                    <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-7.2.7</fr:parent>
                  </fr:frontmatter>
                  <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex> be a complex endowed with a biregular filtration <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex>.
      For <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Gr}_G(L)]]></fr:tex> to be acyclic, it is necessary and sufficient that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex> be acyclic and that the differentials of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex> be strictly compatible with the filtration <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
  
    
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1063</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">#249</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-249.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-7.2.7.1</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:p>This is a particular case of <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.2" href="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.2.xml" taxon="Proposition" number="1.3.2" />.</fr:p>
    </fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
  
</fr:mainmatter>
                  <fr:backmatter />
                </fr:tree>
                <fr:p>Applying <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-7.2.7.1" href="hodge-theory-iii-7.2.7.1.xml" taxon="Lemma" number="7.2.7.1" />, taking <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L]]></fr:tex> to be the complex
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       0       \to  \operatorname {H}(F^pK)       \to  \operatorname {H}(K)       \to  \operatorname {H}(K/F^pK)       \to  0,     ]]></fr:tex>
    we see that:

    
 <html:ol xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(a) &quot;">
        This sequence is exact, i.e. the differentials of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex> are strictly compatible with the filtration <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex>;
      </html:li>


      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(b) &quot;">
        the filtration of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}(F^pK)]]></fr:tex> induced by the filtration <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[W]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F^pK]]></fr:tex> coincides with the filtration induced by the filtration <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[W]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}(K)]]></fr:tex>;
      </html:li>


      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(c) &quot;">
        an analogous statement holds for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K/F^pK]]></fr:tex>.
      </html:li>

    </html:ol></fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:p>In conclusion:</fr:p>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>1068</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-7.2.8</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-7.2.8.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>7.2.8</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-7.2</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(K,F,W)]]></fr:tex> satisfies <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-7.2.2" href="hodge-theory-iii-7.2.2.xml" taxon="Condition" number="7.2.2" /> for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r_0=\infty ]]></fr:tex>, then the spectral sequence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E(K,F)]]></fr:tex> degenerates (<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_1=E_\infty ]]></fr:tex>).
    Furthermore, we have an isomorphism of spectral sequences
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       \operatorname {Gr}_F^p(E_\bullet (K,W))       \simeq  E_\bullet (\operatorname {Gr}_F^pK,W).     ]]></fr:tex></fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:backmatter />
    </fr:tree>
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
      <fr:frontmatter>
        <fr:title text="Related">Related</fr:title>
        <fr:authors />
      </fr:frontmatter>
      <fr:mainmatter>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>2685</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-ii-1.3.13</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>hodge-theory-ii-1.3.13.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:number>1.3.13</fr:number>
            <fr:parent>hodge-theory-ii-1.3</fr:parent>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
 <html:ol xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
    
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(i) &quot;">
      For the first direct filtration, the morphisms <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d_r]]></fr:tex> are compatible with the filtrations.
      If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_{r+1}^{pq}]]></fr:tex> is considered as a quotient of a sub-object of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_r^{pq}]]></fr:tex>, then the first direct filtration on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_{r+1}^{pq}]]></fr:tex> is finer than the filtration <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F']]></fr:tex> induced by the first direct filtration on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_r^{pq}]]></fr:tex>Y we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F_d(E_{r+1}^{pq})\subset  F'(E_{r+1}^{pq})]]></fr:tex>.
    </html:li>


    
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(ii) &quot;">
      Dually, the morphisms <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d_r]]></fr:tex> are compatible with the second direct filtration, and the second direct filtration on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_{r+1}^{pq}]]></fr:tex> is less fine than the filtration induced by that of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_r^{pq}]]></fr:tex>.
    </html:li>


    
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(iii) &quot;">
      <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F_d(E_r^{pq})\subset  F_r(E_r^{pq})\subset  F_{d^*}(E_r^{pq})]]></fr:tex>.
    </html:li>


    
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(iv) &quot;">
      On <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_\infty ^{pq}]]></fr:tex>, the filtration induced by the filtration <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^\bullet (K)]]></fr:tex> <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.12" href="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.12.xml" number="1.3.12" /> is finer than the first direct filtration and less fine than the second.
    </html:li>

  </html:ol>

  
    
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>957</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">#285</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-285.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:parent>hodge-theory-ii-1.3.13</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>Claim (i) is evident, (ii) is its dual, and (iii) follows by induction.
      The first claim of (iv) is easy to verify, and the second is its dual.</fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
  
</fr:mainmatter>
